In [[real estate]], an '''erf''' (pl. erven) is the legal term used in [[Namibia]], [[South Africa]] and [[Swaziland]] to describe a piece of land registered in a deeds registry as an erf, [[Land lot|lot]], plot or stand. The term is of [[Afrikaans]] origin.
Section 102 of the South African Deeds Registries Act, 1937 <ref>[http://www.acts.co.za/deeds-registries-act-1937/deeds_registries_act__1937_act South African Deeds Registries Act, 1937 (Act No. 47 of 1937)] Retrieved 21 December 2016</ref> provides the following definition: {{block quote|“erf” means every piece of land registered as an erf, lot, plot or stand in a deeds registry, and includes every defined portion, not intended to be a public place, of a piece of land laid out as a township, whether or not it has been formally recognized, approved or proclaimed as such.}}
Section 1 of the Namibian Deeds Registries Act, 2015 (Act No. 14 of 2015)<ref>[http://www.lac.org.na/laws/2015/5913.pdf Namibian Deeds Registries Act, 2015 (Act No. 14 of 2015)] Retrieved 21 December 2016</ref> gives an identical definition.
