{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}

'''Xie Wanjun''' ({{zh|s=谢万军|t=謝萬軍|p=Xiè Wànjūn|w=Hsieh Wan-chün}}) (born July 10, 1967) a political activist that fled to the [[United States]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/409125.stm|title=World: Asia-Pacific Chinese dissident arrives in US|work=BBC NEWS|date=1 August 1999|access-date=14 May 2017}}</ref> He is currently the chairman of [[China Democracy Party]]. He was an active student during the [[Tiananmen Square Protests of 1989]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1989/05/19/world/hunger-strikers-heart-of-china-protest.html|title=Hunger Strikers, Heart of China Protest|work=The New York Times|date=19 May 1989|access-date=14 May 2017}}</ref> On October 17, 1996, he led an anti-Japan protest and was imprisoned for a month. In August 1997, he tried to apply a trade union in [[Shanghai]] but he was expelled from Shanghai. He was one of the founding members of China Democracy Party in 1998, and was elected to the central committee in February 1999, he escaped from China in April 1999, he then fled to [[Russia]] then the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://old.themoscowtimes.com/sitemap/free/1999/8/article/chinese-dissident-leaves-vladivostok-for-new-york/274173.html|title=Chinese Dissident Leaves Vladivostok for New York|work=The Moscow Times|date=3 August 1999|access-date=14 May 2017}}</ref>

